1 Data: Simulate an example data set

To illustrate SMOFA we simulate a small example data set with 4 different views and a single covariate using make_example_data. The simulation is based on 4 factors, two of which vary smoothly along the covariate (with different lengthscales) and two are independent of the covariate. To mimic a situation where we only have incomplete data on the samples we mask 50% of the samples on average per view.

set.seed(2020)

# number of views and samples
M <- 4
N <- 400

# generate example data
dd <- make_example_data(n_samples = N, n_features = 500,
                        n_views = M, lscales = c(100, 30, 0,0))

# mask some samples in some views
mask <- sample(1:N, N*0.1*M, replace = TRUE)
# mask <- split(mask, 1:M)
# dd$data <- lapply(1:M, function(m) {
#   mdd <- dd$data[[m]]
#   mdd[, mask[[m]]] <- NA
#   mdd
#   })

2 SMOFA

2.1 Create a SMOFA object

To create a SMOFA objevt we need to specify the training data and (optionally) the covariates for pattern detection and inerence of smooth factors. Here, sample_cov is a matrix with samples in columns and covariates in rows. The sample order must match the order in data columns. Alternatively, a data frame can be provided containung one sample columns with samples names matching the sample names in the data.

sm <- create_smofa(data = dd$data, sample_cov = dd$sample_cov)
sm
## Untrained SMOFA model with the following characteristics: 
##  Number of views: 4 
##  Views names: view_1 view_2 view_3 view_4 
##  Number of features (per view): 500 500 500 500 
##  Number of covariates: 1 
##  Number of samples: 400
plot_data_overview(sm)

2.2 Prepare a SMOFA object

Before training, we can specify various options for the model, the training and the data preprocessing. If no options are specified, the model will use the default options. See also get_default_data_options, get_default_model_options and get_default_training_options to have a look at the defaults and change them where required. Here, we drop factors that explain less than 1% of variance in the data starting from 10 factors. We use a grid of 50 points to optimise the lengthscale of each factor and make use of sparse Gaussian process inference by setting sparseGP to TRUE. This results in a faster inference compared to modelling the full covariance matrix.

train_opt <- get_default_training_options(sm)
train_opt$drop_factor_threshold <- 0.01
train_opt$seed <- 1234567
train_opt$maxiter <- 300
model_opts <- get_default_model_options(sm)
model_opts$num_factors <- 10
model_opts$mv_Znode <- TRUE
model_opts$sparseGP <- TRUE
model_opts$n_inducing <- 0.5*N
model_opts$n_grid <- 50
model_opts$seed_inducing <- 1234567
sm <- prepare_smofa(sm, training_options = train_opt, model_options = model_opts)

2.3 Run SMOFA

Now, the SMOFA object is ready for training. Using run_smofa we can fit the model, which is saves in the file specified as outfile. If none is specified the output is only saved in a temporary location.

sm <- run_smofa(sm)
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node Y"
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node Tau"
## [1] "DEV :: NOTE: There are no expectations for the node Y"

2.4 Down-stream analysis

2.4.1 Variance explained per factor

Using plot_variance_explained we can explore which factor is active in which view. plot_factor_cor shows us whether the factors are correlated.

plot_variance_explained(sm,plot_total = T)

r <- plot_factor_cor(sm)

### Relate factors to the covariate The SMOFA model has learnt lenghtscales for each factor that tell us how smoohtly the factor varys along the covariate. A lengthscale of 0 means that the factor captures variation independent of the covariate, a high value tells us that this factor varys very smoothly along the covariate. In this example, we find two factors that are non-smooth and one smooth factor. Using plot_factors_vs_cov we can plot the factors along the covariate to visualize this relationship.

get_lengthscales(sm)
##   Factor1   Factor2   Factor3   Factor4 
##  0.000000  0.000000 25.034474  2.618293
plot_factors_vs_cov(sm, scale = TRUE)

We can compare this to the factors that were simulated:

df <- data.frame(dd$Z, get_covariates(sm, as.data.frame = T))
df <- gather(df, key = "factor", value = "value", starts_with("simulated_factor"))
ggplot(df, aes(x =covariate_1, y = value)) + geom_point() + facet_grid(~factor)

2.4.2 Exploration of weights

As with MOFA(+) we can now look deeper into the meaning of these factors by exploring the weigths or performing feature set enrichment analysis.

# plot_weights(sm, factors = 4, view = 1)
# plot_top_weights(sm, factors = 3, view = 2)

3 Alternative options and comparisons

3.1 Standard MOFA(+) (without covariates)

When we do not specify any sample covariates or set GP_factors to FALSE, the model falls back to the standard MOFA model. We train this here as a comparison.

# create new SMOFA object (note we could also set sample_cov to NULL)
sm_nocov <- create_smofa(data = dd$data, sample_cov = dd$sample_cov)
## Creating SMOFA object from a list of matrices (features as rows, sample as columns)...
## Warning in .add_sample_cov(object, sample_cov, scale_cov): No sample names
## provided in data or sample_cov or both - please make sure that the order of
## sample covariates matches the order of columns in the data matrix.
## No sample names in covariates - using the sample names provided in data for covariates.
## Warning in quality_control(object): You have features which do not contain a
## single observation, consider removing them...
## Warning in quality_control(object): There are duplicated features names across different views. We will add the suffix *_view* only for those features 
##             Example: if you have both TP53 in mRNA and mutation data it will be renamed to TP53_mRNA, TP53_mutation
# set options
train_opt <- get_default_training_options(sm_nocov)
train_opt$drop_factor_threshold <- 0.01
train_opt$seed <- 1234567
model_opts <- get_default_model_options(sm_nocov)
model_opts$num_factors <- 10
model_opts$GP_factors <- FALSE

# Prepare and train the SMOFA object
sm_nocov <- prepare_smofa(sm_nocov, training_options = train_opt, model_options = model_opts)
## Checking data options...
## No data options specified, using default...
## Checking training options...
## Checking model options...
sm_nocov <- run_smofa(sm_nocov)
## Warning in run_smofa(sm_nocov): No output filename provided. Using /tmp/SMOFA_20200217-141642.hdf5 to store the trained model.

3.1.1 Variance explained per factor

As above, we use plot_variance_explained to explore which factor is active in which view. plot_factor_cor shows us whether the factors are correlated.

plot_variance_explained(sm_nocov,plot_total = T)

r <- plot_factor_cor(sm_nocov)

3.1.2 Relate factors to the covariate

Without covariates (using GP_factors = FALSE), the SMOFA model does not learn lenghtscales for a factor. However, we can still correlate a posterior the covariate to the learnt factors. We note, that these are less smooth than the factors learnt with covariates and samples with missing values are not placed correctly.

plot_factors_vs_cov(sm_nocov, scale = TRUE)

3.2 Comparison of factor smoothness between models

Compare simulated and inferred factors including the posterior variance of factor values (illustrating the uncertainty of the factor values). Note that factors can be flipped (mirrored at the x-axis) and in a different order compared to the simulated factors due to the symmetry of the model.

df <- data.frame(dd$Z, get_covariates(sm, as.data.frame = T))
df <- gather(df, key = "factor", value = "value", starts_with("simulated_factor"))
ggplot(df, aes(x =covariate_1, y = value)) + geom_point() + facet_grid(~factor)

plot_factors_vs_cov(sm, scale = TRUE, show_variance = TRUE)

# plot_factors_vs_cov(sm_univ, scale = TRUE, show_variance = TRUE)
plot_factors_vs_cov(sm_nocov, scale = TRUE, show_variance = TRUE)
